Interesting question for everyone. So for a month and a half before my A1C checkup last week I was on 3 units of 70/30 and the doctor a month before added metformin 500mg twice a day  to start the transition of getting off the insulin. Then the 4.8 A1C from a 14.8 came back and like we planned we stopped the insulin and now I‚Äôve been on metformin 1000mg twice a day. I was told the numbers would just slightly increase over the next few days as the result of the insulin being withdrawn.  My numbers are still running good and not changing anything up.  I‚Äôm seeing more of a flattening out in my numbers and it‚Äôs been now 5 days since I‚Äôve been on insulin.   I was told that I‚Äôm gonna see numbers I‚Äôm not used to yet I‚Äôm familiar with even with being on the insulin. So today as you can see my fasting was 103 compared to all the other days you see.    Just looking to see if any of you have experienced the transition for insulin to not being on it. Also I‚Äôm gonna start not checking the fasting and 2 hour after meals every meal soon. Maybe just my fasting and the doc said one day check 2 hours after breakfast or lunch or dinner depending on schedule.

Ham and Asparagus QuicheEquipment10-inch pie plateFrying panMedium bowlcutting boardIngredients1 recipe Flaky Low Carb Pie Crust (or your favorite or omit)1/2 pound asparagus (8 oz)1 cup ham cubed (6 oz)1/4 cup onion chopped (1 oz)1 tbsp butter2 cups Gruyere cheese shredded (8 oz)5 large eggs1 cup heavy cream (8 fl oz)1/4 cup water (4 fl oz)1/4 tsp salt1/4 tsp white pepperInstructionsPrepare the pie crust per instructions. While the dough chills, move on to the preparation of the quiche ingredients (below). Then roll out the dough and line a 10-inch pie plate, wrap and chill until needed. [NOTE: The pie crust dough will keep in the refrigerator for several days or can be frozen for up to 3 months.]Preheat oven to 375 F and place racks in the middle and lowest positions.With a vegetable peeler lightly peel the asparagus and trim to half the diameter of the pie plate. Slice any remaining asparagus into bite sized pieces. Chop the onion and dice the ham. Grate the cheese and set aside.To a medium pan over medium heat, add 1 tbsp of butter and saute the sliced asparagus, onion and ham until the onion begins to soften and the ham develops some color. Stir in the asparagus spears and turn off the heat to cool. Then remove the spears to use on top of the quicheAdd the eggs, cream, water, thyme, salt and white pepper into a medium bowl. Beat with a hand mixer until frothy.Layer 1/3 of the cheese into the pie plate, followed by 1/3 of the ham mixture. Continue layering twice more. Pour the custard mixture over the quiche and arrange the asparagus spears on top, radiating out from the middle of the quiche.Bake the quiche on the lowest rack for approximately 30 then move to the middle rack and cook about 10 minutes more. The quiche is done when it is just barely set in the middle but still a little soft. (I like mine cooked more so I remove it when it is completely cooked and firm in the middle.) Place under the broiler to brown the top to your liking.Serve slightly warm or at room temperature with a green salad or grilled vegetables. Cover leftovers and refrigerate up to 5 days or freeze up to 3 months. I reheat a slice at a time, uncovered, in the microwave for about a minute.5.5 G NET CARBS PER SLICENotesCalories: 319, Fat: 27 g, Carbs: 3 g, Fiber: 1 g, Sugar: 1 g, Protein: 18 g, NET CARBS FOR QUICHE ONLY: 2 g per 1 slice NUTRITIONAL INFO FOR QUICHE WITHOUT CRUST NutritionServing: 1slice | Calories: 493kcal | Carbohydrates: 7.5g | Protein: 22.5g | Fat: 42g | Cholesterol: 224mg | Sodium: 501mg | Potassium: 166mg | Fiber: 3.8g | Sugar: 1.6g | Vitamin A: 2928IU | Vitamin C: 2mg | Calcium: 757mg | Iron: 5.8mg

Bragging a little.  I've been doing Keto for a while now.  I've gone from 330lbs to 255lbs, A1C has gone from 9.7 to 5.4 and my doctor cut my medicine in half.  I'm trying to keep my weight going down and I've had my ups and downs but have been strict keto for 2 months now to get past my plateau to ge to my goal of 225.  I've been big all my life or so it seems.  I've been over 300 since high school and now I'm 40. so this has been a big change.  At my biggest I was wearing a 5-6XL shirt and a 46 waist.  I'm at 2xl shirts and a 36 inch waist (I have no butt).  Now I'm experiencing low glucose events and have a continuous monitor to help me.  I'm looking to see if people have totally got off the meds on Keto and to see if the struggle is worth it in the end.  I like my beer and pasta and this has been a real challenge for me.

I just wanted to thank everybody for this group and give some encouragement to the newbies. I am a newbie too. I was diagnosed on 6/16 and began this WOE (way of eating) on 6/17. I was sick to my stomach for the first week and not feeling that great the following week. However, I now feel great and have lost a total of 10 pounds in under 3 weeks. Five of those pounds were over the last 4 days! I lost 2 pounds yesterday and a pound per day the 3 days before! It didn‚Äôt start off very well with the sickness and no weight loss right away, but now the pounds are just falling off and I‚Äôm feeling AWESOME! I‚Äôm really starting to think that the diabetes was a blessing. It made me change everything, from my way of eating to mindset. Hang in there newbies and give it your all, it gets better quick and is so worth it!.. Now to start getting serious with some exercise üí™
